Context the ADR itself doesn't capture:

**Why this exists at all.** The previous attempt (PR #98, spike/wanix-agents, +13,197 lines) discovered the right architectural bet mid-branch — a pivot from Wanix (browser-based) to pi-agent + container2wasm — but accumulated failing Integration Tests, a processor rewrite that drifted off-scope, and zero git notes across 30+ commits. This ADR exists as the anchor so the re-do has something to snap back to when scope creeps.

**Why wasmtime and not another runtime.** Verified against c2w's README at commit time: c2w's "WASI Runtimes Integration Status" table ranks wasmtime first with full green-check coverage for stdio/mapdir/networking; wasmer and wasmedge are explicitly flagged WIP ("stdin unsupported"). wasmtime is also Rust-native (`cargo add wasmtime wasmtime-wasi`), has stable WASIp2, and is production-used by Fastly/Shopify/Microsoft. Epoch interruption + per-agent `Store` isolation gives us the rollback primitive for free — no need for a full VM snapshot. wasmer was the runner-up but its WASIX-first posture made it the wrong tool for a c2w host.

**Why Docker removal is complete, not a demotion.** First draft of this ADR kept Docker as an optional fallback. User pushed back explicitly: "get rid of Docker support completely. I think that will simplify things." Rationale: half the isolation code to maintain, removes the worst cross-platform quirks (Docker Desktop macOS filesystem perf, WSL2, GPU passthrough matrices), and forces us to confront c2w's rough edges rather than hide behind Docker. Existing Docker users are frozen on pre-ADR-023 releases; no migration compatibility shim.

**Why the sidecar owns all LLM traffic.** The non-obvious decision here is that harnesses are forbidden from holding API keys or picking providers directly. This is what makes the "budget downgrade to local" story architectural rather than per-harness cooperation. Any harness that insists on a native SDK gets a per-provider OpenAI-compatible shim from the sidecar, not direct provider access. This was a user call, not something I proposed — he framed it as "transparent to the harness" and "supporting multiple backends, falling back to a local model if over budget."

**What's not in the ADR but is implied:** the built-in Claude-SDK backend needs to be retrofitted onto the new Harness trait, which means the existing processor + tool execution code reorganizes around the same abstraction pi uses. That's a meaningful refactor and should be its own chunk of work, not a side effect of implementing PiHarness.

**Scope-drift mitigation.** The 7 MVP exit criteria are intentionally concrete (fresh install, specific budget cap, specific failure mode, specific rollback proof). If implementation work starts adding things not traceable to one of those 7 criteria, it's out of scope for V1 and goes to a follow-up ADR. This is the anti-spike-failure lever.
